NAME
    printf - format and print data

SYNOPSIS
    printf <format> [arguments...]

DESCRIPTION
    Formats and prints arguments according to a format string.
    Unlike echo, printf does not append a newline automatically.

FORMAT SPECIFIERS
    %s              String
    %d, %i          Signed decimal integer
    %u              Unsigned decimal integer
    %o              Octal
    %x, %X          Hexadecimal (lower/upper case)
    %f              Floating point decimal
    %e, %E          Scientific notation
    %g, %G          Shorter of %f or %e
    %c              Single character
    %%              Literal percent sign

WIDTH AND PRECISION
    %10s            Right-align in 10 characters
    %-10s           Left-align in 10 characters
    %010d           Zero-pad to 10 digits
    %.2f            2 decimal places
    %10.2f          Width 10, 2 decimal places
    %*s             Width from argument

FLAGS
    -               Left-align
    +               Show sign for positive numbers
    (space)         Space before positive numbers
    #               Alternate form (0x for hex, etc.)
    0               Zero-pad

ESCAPE SEQUENCES
    \\              Backslash
    \n              Newline
    \t              Tab
    \r              Carriage return
    \xHH            Hex byte
    \0NNN           Octal byte

EXAMPLES
    printf "Hello %s\n" world
        Output: Hello world

    printf "%d + %d = %d\n" 1 2 3
        Output: 1 + 2 = 3

    printf "%-10s %5d\n" "Name" 42
        Output: Name           42

    printf "%08x\n" 255
        Output: 000000ff

    printf "%.2f\n" 3.14159
        Output: 3.14

    printf "%s\t%s\n" "col1" "col2"
        Tab-separated columns

    printf "%'d\n" 1000000
        Output: 1,000,000

SEE ALSO
    echo
